<section xml:id="sec_arith_triangle">
  <title>The Arithmetic Triangle</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <xref ref="ch_counting">In</xref>,
      we saw three counting techniques:
      steps (where we multiply), cases
      (where we add),
      and subsets
      (where we use binomial coefficients).
      <xref ref="sec_model_sum_prod">In</xref>
      and <xref ref="sec_sum_conj"></xref>,
      we worked with sums and products.
      In this section, we revisit the binomial coefficients,
      defined in <xref ref="defn_binomial_coeff"></xref>, which are
      <me>
        \binom{n}{k} = \text{ the number of ways to select a subset of }  k \text{ elements from a set of }  n \text{ elements }
      </me>
      for nonnegative integers <m>n</m> and <m>k</m>.
      We introduce the arithmetic triangle.<fn>
      The arithmetic triangle was formerly known as Pascal's triangle,
      and the generic name honors that the arithmetic triangle was known in Asia,
      the middle East,
      and Europe countries centuries before Pascal lived.
      </fn> We examine the recursion that generates the arithmetic triangle,
      which is useful for computation,
      and search for patterns among the binomial coefficients,
      including summations.
      We also explain the origin of the name
      <q>binomial coefficient</q>
      and we derive an explicit formula for the binomial coefficients which is of theoretical use.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_arith_triangle">
    <title>\subarithtri</title>
    <p>
      How do we calculate the value of <m>\binom{n}{k}</m>?
      Let's first look at an example using the definition.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_eval_7choose4">
      <title>Evaluating a binomial coefficient by listing subsets</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate <m>\binom{7}{4}</m> without using computational technology.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <xref ref="defn_binomial_coeff">By</xref>,
          we can count all 4-element subsets of a set with seven elements,
          say <m>\{1,2,3,4,5,6,7\}</m>.
          We list these subsets in <xref ref="table_subset_list_7choose4"></xref>.
          There are 35 subsets, so <m>\binom{7}{4}=35</m>.
        </p>
        <table xml:id="table_subset_list_7choose4">
          <title>The 4-element subsets of the set <m>\{1,2,3,4,5,6,7\}</m></title>
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\{1,2,3,4\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,2,3,5\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,2,3,6\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,2,3,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,2,4,5\}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\{1,2,4,6\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,2,4,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,2,5,6\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,2,5,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,2,6,7\}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\{1,3,4,5\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,3,4,6\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,3,4,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,3,5,6\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,3,5,7\}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\{1,3,6,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,4,5,6\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,4,5,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,4,6,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{1,5,6,7\}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\{2,3,4,5\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{2,3,4,6\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{2,3,4,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{2,3,5,6\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{2,3,5,7\}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\{2,3,6,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{2,4,5,6\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{2,4,5,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{2,4,6,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{2,5,6,7\}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\{3,4,5,6\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{3,4,5,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{3,4,6,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{3,5,6,7\}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\{4,5,6,7\}</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      There are some values of binomial coefficients that we can compute from the definition.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_border_values_binom_coeffs">
      <title>Border values of binomial coefficients</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Explain why <m>\binom{n}{0}=1</m> and
                <m>\binom{n}{n}=1</m> using the definition of the binomial coefficients.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Given a set with <m>n</m> elements,
                    there is only one 0-element subsets,
                    namely the empty set <m>\varnothing</m>.
                    Similarly, there is only one <m>n</m>-element subset, namely the set itself.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Explain why <m>\binom{n}{1}=n</m> using the definition of the binomial coefficients.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Given a set with <m>n</m> elements,
                    there are <m>n</m> 1-element subsets,
                    one for each element of the set.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Listing the <m>k</m>-element subsets of a set with <m>n</m> elements is tedious,
      even for small values of <m>n</m> and <m>k</m>,
      and it is impractical for any larger values.
      We would like a more efficient way to calculate the values of
      <m>\binom{n}{k}</m> by hand for small values of <m>n</m> and <m>k</m>.
      For larger values,
      we seek a recursive definition to compute the values.
      We begin with a way to list binomial coefficients in a triangular array.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_arith_triangle">
      <title>The arithmetic triangle</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>arithmetic triangle</term>
          is an array of binomial coefficients,
          where each row has, in order,
          the values <m>\binom{n}{k}</m>,
          for <m>k=0,1,2, \ldots, n</m>.
          For example,
          the first row has a single value, <m>\binom{0}{0}=1</m>.
          The second row has, in order,
          the values <m>\binom{1}{0}=1</m> and <m>\binom{1}{1}=1</m>.
          The third row has, in order,
          the values <m>\binom{2}{0}=1</m>,
          <m>\binom{2}{1}=2</m>, and <m>\binom{2}{2}=1</m>.
          END<xref ref="figure_arith_tri_expanded"></xref>
          shows the first eight rows of the expanded version of the arithmetic triangle that includes the binomial coefficients and their values.
          <xref ref="figure_arith_tri_standard"></xref>
          shows the first eight rows of the standard version that lists only the values.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="figure_arith_tri_expanded">
          <caption>The first eight rows of the  arithmetic triangle in expanded format.</caption>
          <me>
            \binom{0}{0}=1
          </me>
          <me>
            \binom{1}{0}=1 \hspace{.23in} \binom{1}{1}=1
          </me>
          <me>
            \binom{2}{0}=1 \hspace{.23in} \binom{2}{1}=2 \hspace{.23in} \binom{2}{2}=1
          </me>
          <me>
            \binom{3}{0}=1 \hspace{.23in} \binom{3}{1}=3 \hspace{.23in} \binom{3}{2}=3\hspace{.23in} \binom{3}{3}=1
          </me>
          <me>
            \binom{4}{0}=1 \hspace{.23in} \binom{4}{1}=4 \hspace{.23in} \binom{4}{2}=6 \hspace{.23in} \binom{4}{3}=4\hspace{.23in} \binom{4}{4}=1
          </me>
          <me>
            \binom{5}{0}=1 \hspace{.23in} \binom{5}{1}=5 \hspace{.23in} \binom{5}{2}=10 \hspace{.23in} \binom{5}{3}=10\hspace{.23in} \binom{5}{4}=5\hspace{.23in} \binom{5}{5}=1
          </me>
          <me>
            \binom{6}{0}=1 \hspace{.23in} \binom{6}{1}=6\hspace{.23in} \binom{6}{2}=15 \hspace{.23in} \binom{6}{3}=20\hspace{.23in} \binom{6}{4}=15\hspace{.23in} \binom{6}{5}=6\hspace{.23in} \binom{6}{6}=1
          </me>
          <me>
            \binom{7}{0}=1 \hspace{.23in} \binom{7}{1}=7\hspace{.23in} \binom{7}{2}=21 \hspace{.23in} \binom{7}{3}=35\hspace{.23in} \binom{7}{4}=35\hspace{.23in} \binom{7}{5}=21\hspace{.23in} \binom{7}{6}=7\hspace{.23in} \binom{7}{7}=1
          </me>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="figure_arith_tri_standard">
          <caption>The first eight rows of the  arithmetic triangle in standard format.</caption>
          <me>
            1
          </me>
          <me>
            1 \hspace{.23in} 1
          </me>
          <me>
            1 \hspace{.23in} 2 \hspace{.23in} 1
          </me>
          <me>
            1 \hspace{.23in} 3 \hspace{.23in} 3\hspace{.23in} 1
          </me>
          <me>
            1 \hspace{.23in} 4 \hspace{.23in} 6 \hspace{.23in} 4\hspace{.23in}1
          </me>
          <me>
            1 \hspace{.23in} 5 \hspace{.23in} 10 \hspace{.23in} 10\hspace{.23in} 5\hspace{.23in} 1
          </me>
          <me>
            1 \hspace{.23in} 6\hspace{.23in} 15 \hspace{.23in} 20\hspace{.23in}15\hspace{.23in} 6\hspace{.23in} 1
          </me>
          <me>
            1 \hspace{.23in} 7\hspace{.23in} 21 \hspace{.23in} 35\hspace{.23in} 35\hspace{.23in}21\hspace{.23in} 7\hspace{.23in} 1
          </me>
        </figure>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      We can use the arithmetic triangle to evaluate binomial coefficients.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_using_arith_tri_eval">
      <title>Using the arithmetic triangle to evaluate binomial coefficients</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the arithmetic triangle drawn in <xref ref="figure_arith_tri_standard"></xref>
          to evaluate each binomial coefficient.
          If you are not sure where to look in the triangle,
          refer to <xref ref="figure_arith_tri_expanded"></xref>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \binom{4}{2}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    The row that starts with 1, 4 lists
                    <me>
                      \binom{4}{0}=1, \binom{4}{1}=4, \binom{4}{2}=6, \ldots
                    </me>.
                    This answer agrees with our list of the 2-element subsets of
                    <m>\{1,2,3,4\}</m> from <xref ref="exam_four_choose_k"></xref>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \binom{6}{4}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    The row that starts with 1, 6 lists
                    <m>\displaystyle \binom{6}{k}</m> for <m>k=0, 1, 2, 3, 4, \ldots</m>.
                    Because the list begins at <m>k=0</m>,
                    the fifth number in that row gives
                    <me>
                      \displaystyle \binom{6}{4}=15
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Try working with the arithmetic triangle.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_arith_tri">
      <title>The arithmetic triangle</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Copy the first eight rows of the arithmetic triangle.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use the arithmetic triangle to evaluate each of the following binomial coefficients and circle the corresponding entries in the triangle.
              <me>
                \binom{5}{4}, \binom{7}{5}, \binom{3}{0}, \binom{6}{1}, \binom{2}{2}
              </me>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_arith_tri_from6to7">
            <p>
              There is a way to calculate the row that starts with 1, 7 from the row above it.
              Can you see how? (Do not spoil the surprise for others if you already know the answer.) Hint: Each entry of the row is calculated using two nearby entries from the previous row.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_arith_tri_from7to8">
            <p>
              Use the pattern from <xref ref="part_arith_tri_from6to7"/> to write the next row that starts with 1, 8.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_eval_8choosek">
            <p>
              Use your new row to evaluate each of the following binomial coefficients:
              <me>
                \binom{8}{2}, \binom{8}{4}, \binom{8}{5}
              </me>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write a formula for how to calculate the row that stars <m>1, n</m> from the row above it.
              Your formula should be in the form <m>\displaystyle \binom{n}{k} =</m>.
              Hint: The entries from the row above will involve <m>n-1</m> and <m>k</m>s.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Make sure to <xref ref="act_arith_tri">complete</xref>
      before reading on because we are going to share the key observation.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem_generating_arith_triangle">
      <title>Generating the arithmetic triangle</title>
      <p>
        We can generate the arithmetic triangle as follows.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The first row is 1.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The entry in each subsequent row is the sum of the two entries above it in the previous row,
              with the understanding that a missing entry equals zero.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      We state this recursion formally.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_pascals_recursion">
      <title>Recursive definition of the binomial coefficients</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The binomial coefficients can be defined recursively by <m>\binom{n}{0}=\binom{n}{n}=1</m> and
          <me>
            \binom{n}{k}=\binom{n-1}{k-1} + \binom{n-1}{k}
          </me>
          for any nonnegative integer <m>n</m> and integer <m>k=1, \ldots, n-1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Let's see this formula in action.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_arith_tri_row9">
      <title>Adding another row to the arithmetic triangle</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <xref ref="thm_pascals_recursion">Use</xref>
          to write the row of the arithmetic triangle that begins with 1, 8.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We begin with a copy of the row that begins with 1, 7 from <xref ref="figure_arith_tri_standard"></xref>.
          We add neighboring entries to calculate the entries of the next row:
          <me>
            0+1=1  1+7=8 7 +21 = 28 21+35 = 56 35+35=70
          </me>
          <me>
            35+21 = 56 21+7 = 28 7+1 = 8 1 + 0 = 1
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          The result is shown in <xref ref="fig_arith_triangle_recursion"></xref>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig_arith_triangle_recursion">
          <caption>Generating another row of the arithmetic triange.</caption>
          image type not recognized
        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pascal_patterns">
    <title>\subpascalpatterns</title>
    <p>
      There are many patterns that involve binomial coefficients.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_pascals_patterns">
      <title>Looking for patterns in the arithmetic triangle</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_arith_tri_sym_conj">
            <p>
              Do you notice a symmetry in the arithmetic triangle?
              State your observation as a conjecture of the form <m>\binom{n}{k}=\binom{n}{}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_find_row_sum_arith_tri">
            <p>
              Calculate the sum of the entries in each of row of the arithmetic triangle.
              What did you notice?
              State your observation as a conjecture,
              using summation notation for the sum.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_alt_row_sum_arith_tri">
            <p>
              Conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
              <me>
                \sum_{k=0}^n(-1)^k\binom{n}{k}
              </me>
              for <m>n \ge 0</m>.
              Hint:  Calculate the sum when <m>n=3</m> and <m>n=4</m> first.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Let's look at the first two patterns from <xref ref="act_pascals_patterns"></xref>.
      We begin with the left-right symmetry.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_sym_arith_triangle">
      <title>Symmetry in the arithmetic triangle</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For nonnegative integers <m>n</m> and <m>k</m>, we have
          <me>
            \binom{n}{k} = \binom{n}{n-k}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      We can use this theorem to evaluate binomial coefficients.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_using_sym_arith_triangle">
      <title>Using the symmetry in the arithmetic triangle</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>\binom{n}{n-1}</m> for a integer <m>n\ge 1</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We saw in <xref ref="exam_border_values_binom_coeffs"></xref> that <m>\binom{n}{1}=1</m>.
                    Using symmetry <xref ref="thm_sym_arith_triangle"/>, we get
                    <me>
                      \binom{n}{n-1} = \binom{n}{n-(n-1)} = \binom{n}{1} = n
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Explain why <m>\binom{n}{n-2} = \binom{n}{2}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Using symmetry <xref ref="thm_sym_arith_triangle"/>, we get
                    <me>
                      \binom{n}{n-2} = \binom{n}{n-(n-2)}=\binom{n}{2}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Next, let's look at the row sums.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_sum_rows_arith_triangle">
      <title>Sums of rows of the arithmetic triangle</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Calculate the sum of the entries in the eighth row of the arithmetic triangle.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We add the entries to get
                    <me>
                      1+7+21+35+35+21+7+1 =128
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What did you notice?
                Conjecture an explicit formula for the sum.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We notice that
                    <me>
                      \sum_{k=0}^7\binom{7}{k} = 1+7+21+35+35+21+7+1 =128 = 2^7
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    We conjecture that
                    <me>
                      \sum_{k=0}^n\binom{n}{k}=2^n
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Let's state our conjecture.
      We prove it in <xref ref="exer_bin_thm_find_row_sum"></xref>
      and using a different method in <xref ref="sec_sum_proofs"></xref>.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_sum_rows_arith_triangle">
      <title>Sums of rows of the arithmetic triangle</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For nonnegative integers <m>n</m> we have
          <me>
            \sum_{k=0}^n\binom{n}{k}=2^n
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Here is another summation pattern that involves the binomial coefficients.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_hockey_stick">
      <title>Hockey stick</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_hockey_stick2">
              <p>
                Use the arithmetic triangle to evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=2}^5 \binom{k}{2}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <me>
                    \sum_{k=2}^5 \binom{k}{2} = \binom{2}{2} + \binom{3}{2} + \binom{4}{2} + \binom{5}{2} = 1 + 3 + 6 + 10 = 20
                  </me>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_hockey_stick3">
              <p>
                Use the arithmetic triangle to evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=3}^7 \binom{k}{3}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <me>
                    \sum_{k=3}^7 \binom{k}{3} = \binom{3}{3} + \binom{4}{3} + \binom{5}{3} + \binom{6}{3} + \binom{7}{3} = 1 + 4 + 10 + 20 + 35 = 70
                  </me>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Conjecture an explicit formula for the sum <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=m}^n \binom{k}{m}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    From <xref ref="part_hockey_stick2"/> we know
                    <me>
                      \sum_{k=2}^5 \binom{k}{2} = 20 = \binom{6}{3}
                    </me>.
                    From <xref ref="part_hockey_stick3"/> we know
                    <me>
                      \sum_{k=3}^7 \binom{k}{3} = 70 = \binom{8}{4}
                    </me>.
                    Based on these two examples, it is reasonable to conjecture that
                    <me>
                      \sum_{k=m}^n \binom{k}{m} = \binom{n+1}{m+1}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Why is this called the
                <q>hockey stick</q>
                theorem?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    For example,
                    the sum from <xref ref="part_hockey_stick2"/> is highlighted in <xref ref="fig_hockey_stick"></xref>.
                    The shape of the encircling polygon looks like a hockey stick.
                  </p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig_hockey_stick">
                    <caption>An example of a hockey stick sum.</caption>
                    image type not recognized
                  </figure>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_binom_thm">
    <title>\subbinomthm</title>
    <p>
      The binomial coefficients get their name from polynomials involving two variables that have the binomial coefficients as their coefficients.<fn>
      The word
      <q>binomial</q>
      literally means two names, like <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
      </fn> In our first activity,
      we look at polynomials in one variable.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_powers_nplus1">
      <title>Powers of <m>n+1</m></title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_nplus1_squared">
            <p>
              Expand and simplify <m>(n+1)^2</m>.
              Hint: Start by writing <m>(n+1)^2=(n+1)(n+1)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_nplus1_cubed">
            <p>
              Expand and simplify <m>(n+1)^3</m>.
              Hint: Multiply <m>(n+1)</m> times your answer to <xref ref="part_nplus1_squared"/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Check that you found the first two formulas listed here:
              <md>
                <mrow>(n+1)^2 \amp  =n^2+2n+1</mrow>
                <mrow>(n+1)^3 \amp  =n^3 +3n^2+3n+1</mrow>
                <mrow>(n+1)^4 \amp =n^4+4n^3+6n^2+4n+1</mrow>
              </md>
              We provided the third equation so that you have another example.
              Based on these examples,
              what is the connection between <m>(n+1)^m</m> and the binomial coefficients?
              Explain in words.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Conjecture a formula for <m>(n+1)^m</m> using summation notation.
              Hint: The powers on <m>n</m> decrease,
              so try using <m>x^{m-k}</m> in your formula.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      <xref ref="act_powers_nplus1">In</xref>,
      we observe that the coefficients of <m>(n+1)^m</m> are the binomial coefficients.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem_special_case_binomial_formula">
      <title>Special case of the binomial formula</title>
      <p>
        For any integer <m>n</m> and nonnegative integer <m>m</m>, we have
        <me>
          (n+1)^m = \sum_{k=0}^m \binom{m}{k}n^{m-k}
        </me>
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      Let's look at an example.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_using_special_case_binom_formula">
      <title>Using the special case of the binomial formula</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Expand <m>(n+1)^7</m> <xref ref="rem_special_case_binomial_formula">using</xref>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We get
          <md>
            <mrow>(n+1)^7 \amp  = \sum_{k=0}^7n^{7-k}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp  = \binom{7}{0}n^7 + \binom{7}{1}n^6 + \binom{7}{2} n^5 + \binom{7}{3}n^4 + \binom{7}{4} n^3 + \binom{7}{5}n^2+ \binom{7}{6}n + \binom{7}{7}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp  = n^7 + 7n^6 + 21n^5 + 35n^4 + 35n^3 + 21 n^2 + 7n+1</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The coefficients 1, 7, 21, 35, 35, 21, 7, and 1 come from the eighth row of the arithmetic triangle <xref ref="figure_arith_tri_standard"/>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      The pattern works for the sum of two real numbers,
      <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, raised to a nonnegative integer power.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_binomial_thm">
      <title>The binomial theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> and any nonnegative integer <m>m</m>, we have
          <me>
            (x+y)^m = \sum_{k=0}^m\binom{m}{k}x^{m-k}y^k
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Notice that if <m>x=n</m> and <m>y=1</m>,
      then we have the special case in <xref ref="rem_special_case_binomial_formula"></xref>.
      Let's practice using this theorem.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_practice_binom_thm">
      <title>Practice using binomial theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the binomial theorem <xref ref="thm_binomial_thm"/> to expand <m>(x-2)^3</m> and simplify your answer.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Our coefficients come from the row beginning 1, 3 in <xref ref="figure_arith_tri_standard"></xref>.
          We use <m>m=3</m>, <m>x=x</m>,
          and <m>y=-2</m> in the binomial theorem to get
          <me>
            (x+2)^3=1x^3(-2)^0+3x^3(-2)^1+3x^2(-2)^2+1x^0(-2)^3= n^3-6n^2+12n-8
          </me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      We can use the Binomial Theorem to prove an explicit formula for a summation.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_bin_thm_proof">
      <title>Using the Binomial Theorem to prove a sum formula</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the Binomial Theorem <xref ref="thm_binomial_thm"/> to prove our conjecture from <xref ref="act_pascals_patterns"></xref>
          <xref ref="part_alt_row_sum_arith_tri"/>:
          <me>
            \sum_{k=0}^n(-1)^k\binom{n}{k}=0
          </me>
          for <m>n \ge 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We use <m>x=1</m>, <m>y=-1</m>, and <m>m=n</m> to get
          <me>
            (1+(-1))^n=\sum_{k=0}^n\binom{n}{k}1^{n-k}(-1)^k
          </me>.
          When we simplify each side we get
          <me>
            0=\sum_{k=0}^n(-1)^k\binom{n}{k}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_factorial_binomial">
    <title>\subfactorialbinom</title>
    <p>
      When we count,
      we often leave binomial coefficients in our answers.
      If we need an exact value, then we can use computational technology.
      The fastest way to evaluate binomial coefficients by hand and the method that computational technology uses is the recursive formula <xref ref="thm_pascals_recursion"/>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is also an explicit formula for binomial coefficients.
      Although this formula is impractical for large values of <m>n</m> and <m>k</m>,
      it can be useful for theoretical purposes.
      Let's derive that explicit formula.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_formula_binom_coeffs">
      <title>Explicit formula for binomial coefficients</title>
      <p>
        Suppose there are 100 movies and we want to rank our top ten as movie #1, movie #2, <ellipsis/>, movie #10.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              One option is to choose movie #1, and then choose movie #2, and so on.
              How many ways are there to rank the movies this way?
              It is okay to have <ellipsis/> in your answer.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_top_movies_choose_in_order">
            <p>
              Rewrite your answer as a fraction where the numerator is <m>100!</m> and the denominator is another factorial.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_top_movies_choose_then_order">
            <p>
              An alternative way to pick your top ten movies would be to first select the ten movies you like best (Step 1),
              and then to order them from #1 to #10 (Step 2).
              How many ways are there to rank the movies this way?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Since we are counting the same quantity,
              the answers you found in <xref ref="part_top_movies_choose_in_order"/> and <xref ref="part_top_movies_choose_then_order"/> must be equal.
              Write that equation here.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Solve your equation for <m>\binom{100}{10}</m>.
              What formula did we just prove?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Conjecture the explicit formula for <m>\binom{n}{k}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Test your formula by using it to check by hand that <m>\binom{7}{4} = 35</m>,
              as we saw in <xref ref="table_subset_list_7choose4"></xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      <xref ref="act_formula_binom_coeffs">In</xref>
      we derived an explicit formula for the binomial coefficients.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_binom_coeffs_formula">
      <title>Explicit formula for binomial coefficients</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For integers <m>0 \le k \le n</m>, we have
          <me>
            \binom{n}{k} = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Let's look at how we might <xref ref="thm_binom_coeffs_formula">prove</xref> using a combinatorial proof.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_proof_explicit_binom">
      <title>Combinatorial proof of the explicit formula for the binomial coefficients</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use a combinatorial proof <xref ref="pff_comb_proof"/> to <xref ref="thm_binom_coeffs_formula">prove</xref>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <em>Proof.</em> We use a combinatorial proof.
          Consider the following situation there are <m>n</m> movies.
          How many ways are there to rank our top <m>k</m> as movie #1, movie #2, <ellipsis/>, movie #<m>k</m>?
        </p>
        <p>
          First, we have <m>n</m> choices for movie #1, and then <m>n-1</m> choices for movie #2, and so on until <m>n-(k-1)</m> choices for movie #<m>k</m>.
          Note that <m>n-0, n-1, \ldots,
          n-(k-1)</m> is a list of <m>k</m> rankings.
          Since steps multiply <xref ref="thm_steps_multiply"/>, there are
          <me>
            n(n-1)\ldots(n-(k-1))
          </me>
          ways to rank our top <m>k</m> movies.
          We can write this product in terms of factorials.
          There are
          <me>
            n(n-1)\ldots(n-(k-1)) = \frac{n(n-1)\ldots(n-(k-1))(n-k)\ldots(3)(2)(1)} {(n-k)\ldots(3)(2)(1)} = \frac{n!}{(n-k)!}
          </me>
          ways to rank our top <m>k</m> movies.
        </p>
        <p>
          On the other hand, we can first pick the <m>k</m> movies as a set in
          <m>\binom{n}{k}</m> ways and then rank these <m>k</m> movies in <m>k(k-1)\ldots(3)(2)(1) = k!</m> ways.
          Since steps multiply <xref ref="thm_steps_multiply"/>, there are
          <me>
            \binom{n}{k}k!
          </me>
          ways to rank our top <m>k</m> movies.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since we counted the same quantity in two different ways,
          it follows that
          <me>
            \frac{n!}{(n-k)!}=\binom{n}{k}k!
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Dividing each side of this equation by <m>k!</m> we get
          <me>
            \binom{n}{k} = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}
          </me>
          as desired.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      This formula is primarily useful for theoretical examples.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_using_formula_binom_coeffs">
      <title>Using the explicit formula for binomial coefficients</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use the explicit formula for the binomial coefficients <xref ref="thm_binom_coeffs_formula"/> to evaluate <m>\binom{8}{4}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We have <m>n=8</m>, <m>k=4</m> and <m>n-k=8-4=4</m> and so
                    <me>
                      \binom{8}{4} = \frac{8!}{4! 4!} = \frac{8\cdot 7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5 \cdot \cancel{4} \cdot \cancel{3} \cdot \cancel{2} \cdot \cancel{1}} {4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1 \cdot \cancel{4} \cdot \cancel{3} \cdot \cancel{2} \cdot \cancel{1}} = \frac{\cancel{8}\cdot 7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5}{\cancel{4} \cdot 3 \cdot \cancel{2} \cdot 1} = \frac{7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5}{3} =7 \cdot 2 \cdot 5 =70
                    </me>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Looking back <xref ref="exam_arith_tri_row9">at</xref>
                    we confirm <m>\binom{8}{4}=70</m>.
                    Remember that the index begins at <m>k=0</m> so the 5th entry corresponds to <m>k=4</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_nchoose2_formula_again">
              <p>
                Use the explicit formula for the binomial coefficients <xref ref="thm_binom_coeffs_formula"/> to show that
                <me>
                  \binom{n}{2} = \frac{n(n-1)}{2}
                </me>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We have <m>k=2</m> and <m>n-k = n-2</m>.
                    It is useful to note that
                    <me>
                      n! = n(n-1)(n-2)(n-3) \cdots (3)(2)(1) = n(n-1)(n-2)!
                    </me>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Thus,
                    <me>
                      \binom{n}{2} = \frac{n!}{2!(n-2)!} = \frac{n(n-1)(n-2)!}{2(n-2)!} = \frac{n(n-1)\cancel{(n-2)!}}{2\cancel{(n-2)!}} = \frac{n(n-1)}{2}
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use the explicit formula for the binomial coefficients <xref ref="thm_binom_coeffs_formula"/> to prove algebraically that
                <me>
                  \binom{2n}{2} = 2\binom{n}{2} + n^2
                </me>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    First,
                    <me>
                      \displaystyle \binom{2n}{2} = \frac{(2n)!}{2!(2n-2)!} = \frac{(2n)(2n-1)\cancel{(2n-2)!}}{2\cancel{(2n-2)!}} =\frac{\cancel{2}n(2n-1)}{\cancel{2}} = n(2n-1)
                    </me>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Next, using <xref ref="part_nchoose2_formula_again"/> we have
                    <me>
                      2\binom{n}{2} + n^2 = \cancel{2} \frac{n(n-1)}{\cancel{2}} + n^2 = n(n-1)+ n^2 = n^2-n+n^2=2n^2-n = n(2n-1)
                    </me>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Since we got the same answer,
                    it follows that <m>\displaystyle \binom{2n}{2} = 2\binom{n}{2} + n^2</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_arith_triangle">for</xref> \subarithtri</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_arith_tri_eval_small">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the arithmetic triangle from <xref ref="figure_arith_tri_standard"></xref>
            and the next row found in <xref ref="exam_arith_tri_row9"></xref>
            to evaluate the following binomial coefficients:
            <me>
              \binom{8}{1}, \binom{7}{2}, \binom{4}{3}, \binom{4}{4}, \binom{2}{0}, \binom{5}{3}
            </me>.
            Hint: If you are not sure where to look,
            <xref ref="figure_arith_tri_expanded">consult</xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_arith_tri_more_rows">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_arith_tri_11rows">
                <p>
                  Draw the arithmetic triangle from <xref ref="figure_arith_tri_standard"></xref>
                  and <xref ref="thm_pascals_recursion">use</xref>
                  to continue the triangle through the row that begins with 1, 10.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use your answer to <xref ref="part_arith_tri_11rows"/> to evaluate the following binomial coefficients and circle the corresponding entries in the triangle.
                  <me>
                    \binom{9}{4}, \binom{9}{7}, \binom{10}{4}, \binom{10}{5}
                  </me>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_seq_binom_coeffs">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Evaluate the first six terms of each sequence.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle a_n= \binom{n}{3}</m> for <m>n \ge 3</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle b_k = \binom{2k}{3}</m> for <m>k \ge 2</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle c_m = \binom{m+4}{m}</m> for <m>m \ge 0</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_nte_binom_coeffs">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a simple explicit rule that generates each sequence.
            Hint: Write each term as a binomial coefficient.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The sequence <m>a</m> begins <m>1, 3, 6, 10, 15, 21, \ldots</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The sequence <m>b</m> begins <m>1, 4, 10, 20, 35, 56, \ldots</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_arith_tri">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the binomial coefficients count?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to create the first 7-10 rows of the arithmetic triangle <xref ref="thm_pascals_recursion">using</xref>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Which row of the arithmetic triangle and which entry in that row to use to evaluate <m>\binom{n}{k}</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to evaluate or model with sequences involving binomial coefficients?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_nte_binom_coeffs_harder">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a simple explicit rule that generates each sequence.
            Hint: Write each term as a binomial coefficient.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The sequence <m>c</m> begins <m>1, 2, 6, 20, 70, \ldots</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The sequence <m>d</m> begins <m>1, 15, 70, 210, \ldots</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pascal_patterns">for</xref> \subpascalpatterns</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sums_row4_arith_tri">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/> Use the arithmetic triangle to evaluate each sum.
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_sum_sq_row4_arith_tri">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^4\binom{4}{k}^2</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_sum_ktimes_row4_arith_tri">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^4k\binom{4}{k}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_sum_ktimes_sq_row4_arith_tri">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^4k\binom{4}{k}^2</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_div_arith_triangle">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Check that <m>\displaystyle 7\mid \binom{7}{k}</m> for <m>0 \lt k \lt 7</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Does <m>\displaystyle 3\mid \binom{3}{k}</m> for <m>0 \lt k \lt 3</m>?
                  Justify your answer.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Does <m>\displaystyle 4\mid \binom{4}{k}</m> for <m>0 \lt k \lt 4</m>?
                  Justify your answer.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Does <m>\displaystyle 5\mid \binom{5}{k}</m> for <m>0 \lt k \lt 5</m>?
                  Justify your answer.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Which integers <m>n</m> have
                  <m>\displaystyle n \mid \binom{n}{k}</m> for all <m>0 \lt k \lt n</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sums_sq_rows_arith_tri">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Calculate the first four partial sums of <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n\binom{n}{k}^2</m>.
                  Caution: Since the terms we are adding depend on <m>n</m>,
                  you need to find each partial sum on its own.
                  You cannot using the previous partial sum.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Make a conjecture about an explicit formula for the sum <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n\binom{n}{k}^2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sums_ktimes_rows_arith_tri">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Calculate the first four partial sums of <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^nk\binom{n}{k}</m>.
                  Caution: Since the terms we are adding depend on <m>n</m>,
                  you need to find each partial sum on its own.
                  You cannot using the previous partial sum.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Make a conjecture about an explicit formula for the sum <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^nk\binom{n}{k}</m>.
                  Hint: Factor <m>n</m> to see the pattern.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sums_ktimes_sq_rows_arith_tri">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Calculate the first four partial sums of <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^nk\binom{n}{k}^2</m>.
                  Caution: Since the terms we are adding depend on <m>n</m>,
                  you need to find each partial sum on its own.
                  You cannot using the previous partial sum.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Make a conjecture about an explicit formula for the sum <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^nk\binom{n}{k}^2</m>.
                  Hint: Factor <m>n</m> to see the pattern.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_arith_tri_patterns">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why the arithmetic triangle has left-right symmetry?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to evaluate sums involving binomial coefficients?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use partial sums to conjecture an explicit formula for a sum?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the sum of the entries of a row of the arithmetic triangle equals?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_fib_sum_in_arith_tri">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The Fibonacci numbers appear as the sum of integers in the arithmetic triangle.
            Find them and express your answer as <m>F_n=</m> a sum involving binomial coefficients.
            Hint: Look at an angle.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_binom_thm">for</xref> \subbinomthm</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_expand_nplus1_tothe4">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="act_powers_nplus1">In</xref>,
            we found that <m>(n+1)^3=n^3+3n^2+3n+1</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Expand and simplify <m>(n+1)^4</m>.
                  Hint:
                  <me>
                    (n+1)^4=(n+1)(n+1)^3=(n+1)(n^3+3n^2+3n+1)
                  </me>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The coefficients of your answer are in a row of the arithmetic triangle.
                  Which row?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_binom_thm">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the binomial theorem <xref ref="thm_binomial_thm"/> to expand <m>(n+1)^8</m> and simplify your answer.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the binomial theorem <xref ref="thm_binomial_thm"/> to expand <m>(n-1)^4</m> and simplify your answer.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_bin_thm_proof_row_sum_pascal">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the Binomial Theorem to prove
            <me>
              \sum_{k=0}^n \binom{n}{k} = 2^n
            </me>
            for <m>n \ge 0</m>.
            Hint: Expand <m>(1+1)^n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_bin_thm_find_row_sum">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the Binomial Theorem to find an explicit formula for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n 2^k\binom{n}{k}</m> for <m>n \ge 0</m>.
            Hint: Expand <m>(1+2)^n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_binom_thm_xplush">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the binomial theorem <xref ref="thm_binomial_thm"/> to expand the power and simplify your answer.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(x+h)^2</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(x+h)^3</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(x+h)^4</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_binom_thm">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the binomial theorem says?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use the binomial theorem to expand expressions such as <m>(n+1)^4</m> or <m>(n-1)^4</m> without multiplying out by hand?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use the binomial theorem to prove explicit formulas for sums involving binomial coefficients?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_diff_quo">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If you have <xref ref="exer_binom_thm_xplush">completed</xref>,
            then you may use those answers here.
            For each function, evaluate and simplify the difference quotient
            <me>
              \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}
            </me>
            so that there are no fractions.
            Next, evaluate your answer when <m>h=0</m>.
            Your final answer should be an expression involving <m>x</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>f: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}</m> defined by <m>f(x) = x^2</m>.
                  <nbsp/><nbsp/> Hint:  Your work should begin
                  <me>
                    \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}=\frac{(x+h)^2-(x)^2}{h}=
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>f: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}</m> defined by <m>f(x) = x^3</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>f: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}</m> defined by <m>f(x) = x^4</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For readers who have studied calculus,
                  explain why these answers are correct.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_factorial_binomial">for</xref> \subfactorialbinom</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_eval_binom_formula">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="thm_binom_coeffs_formula">Use</xref>
            to evaluate each binomial coefficient by hand.
            Show work.
            You may use computational technology to check.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\binom{12}{3}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\binom{12}{4}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_simplify_binom_formula">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Simplify each binomial coefficient <xref ref="thm_binom_coeffs_formula">using</xref>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\binom{n}{n}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\binom{n}{1}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\binom{n}{n-1}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\binom{n}{3}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_factorial_proof_sym_recursion_pascal">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove each identity algebraically <xref ref="thm_binom_coeffs_formula">using</xref>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <xref ref="thm_sym_arith_triangle"></xref>:
                  <me>
                    \binom{n}{k} = \binom{n}{n-k}
                  </me>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <xref ref="thm_pascals_recursion"></xref>:
                  <me>
                    \binom{n}{k} = \binom{n-1}{k-1} + \binom{n}{k}
                  </me>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_arith_tri_prove_sym">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a combinatorial proof of <xref ref="thm_sym_arith_triangle"></xref>
            <xref ref="pff_comb_proof">using</xref>:
            <me>
              \binom{n}{k} = \binom{n}{n-k}
            </me>.
            Hint: Out of a group of <m>n</m> people,
            pick a group of <m>k</m> people.
            A less direct way to pick the group is to say who is not in the group.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_binom_formula">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the explicit formula for <m>\binom{n}{k}</m> is?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use the explicit formula to evaluate
                  <m>\binom{n}{k}</m> for small values of <m>n</m> and <m>k</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the steps are in a combinatorial proof <xref ref="pff_comb_proof"/>?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_comb_pf_recursion_arith_tri">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write a combinatorial proof of <xref ref="thm_pascals_recursion"></xref>
            <xref ref="pff_comb_proof">using</xref>:
            <me>
              \binom{n}{k} = \binom{n-1}{k-1} + \binom{n}{k}
            </me>.
            Hint: How many <m>k</m>-elements subsets does the set <m>\{1,2,\ldots,n\}</m> have?
            For a less direct count,
            consider cases based on whether or not <m>n</m> is in the subset.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_binom_coeffs_verify_using_factorials">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="thm_binom_coeffs_formula">Use</xref>
            to prove each identity algebraically.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle (n-m)\binom{n}{m} = n \binom{n-1}{m}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \binom{n}{m}\binom{m}{2}=\binom{n}{2}\binom{n-2}{m-2}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
